description:
We have a view that displays resources with color indicating whether or not that 
resource has been modified since a particular instant in time.  The most 
straightforward approach is to get the location of the resource, convert it to a 
file, then use the lastModified method to get the local modified time in 
milliseconds like this:

  getLocalTimestamp(IResource res) {
    IPath loc = res.getLocation(); 
    if (loc == null)
      return 0L;
    return loc.toFile().lastModified();
  }

Unfortunately, this approach is quite slow.  After digging around in Eclipse 
internals, we found that Eclipse caches this information and it can be obtained 
like this:

  getLocalTimestamp(IResource res) {
    if (!(res instanceof Resource))
      return 0L;
    ResourceInfo info = ((Resource) res).getResourceInfo(false, false);
    if (info == null)
      return 0L
    return info.getLocalSyncInfo();
  }

Unfortunately, this approach uses some internal API.  To prove to myself that 
this second approach really made a difference, I wrote a simple test that 
compared the time it took to loop over each resource in the workspace and call 
the lastModified method with the time it took to loop and call the internal 
getLocalSyncInfo method.  The results were dramatic:

  9036 resources
  3766 milliseconds elapse time when calling lastModified
  140 milliseconds elapse time when calling getLocalSyncTime

This 30x difference in speed proved to me that we need a public API for this so 
that our view will feel snappy rather than sluggish.  To this end I have 
attached a patch based upon the Eclipse 3.0 head stream that creates a new 
getLocalTimestamp method in both IResource and Resource to obtain this 
information via public API.  

Please consider these modifications for inclusion in the Eclipse 3.0 M2 build.

