Since linked resources are entirely possible, we should review all uses of the 
following:

IWorkspaceRoot root= ResourcesPlugin.getWorkspace().getRoot();
IFile file= root.getFileForLocation(filePath);

to ensure that we should not better be using 
IWorkspaceRoot root= ResourcesPlugin.getWorkspace().getRoot();
IFile[] files= root.findFilesForLocation(filePath);

As an example of this bug, consider JUnit tests for Update (i.e. 
TestInstall.java)

In one test, we attempt to install a feature to a configured site at the 
TARGET_FILE_SITE location:
<i>
TestInstall.java:</i>
ISite localSite = SiteManager.getSite(TARGET_FILE_SITE);
localSite.install(remoteFeature, null, null);

But, if the localSite does not exist and/or is not a configured site, we use 
the first configured site we can find (usually the current install):
<i>InstallCommand.java</i>
IConfiguredSite[] sites = getConfiguration().getConfiguredSites();
if (targetSite == null) {
    for (int i = 0; i < sites.length; i++) {
	if (sites[i].isProductSite()) {
		targetSite = sites[i];
		break;
	}
     }
}

Instead of going to the the current installation directory, we should just 
create the configured site.

i.e. Fix for this specific problem would be:

File file = new File(TARGET_FILE_SITE.getFile());
ILocalSite local = SiteManager.getLocalSite();
IInstallConfiguration currentConfig = local.getCurrentConfiguration();
file.mkdirs();
IConfiguredSite configuredSite = currentConfig.createConfiguredSite(file);
currentConfig.addConfiguredSite(configuredSite);

***Please note this will throw exceptions if TARGET_FILE_SITE is a location in 
an existing configured site.

